problem:
A 0.25-kg skeet (clay target) is fired at an angle of 28$^\circ$ to the horizontal with a speed of 25 m/s. When it reaches the maximum height, $h$, it is hit from below by a 15-g pellet traveling vertically upward at a speed of 230 m/s. The pellet is embedded in the skeet. (a) How much higher, $\Delta h$, does the skeet go up? (b) How much extra distance, $\Delta x$, does the skeet travel because of the collision?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.25]{pellet}
    \end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item We first use conservation of momentum in the inelastic collision to find the speed immediately after being hit. This is $$v=\frac{0.25\cdot 0+0.015\cdot 230}{0.25+0.015}=13\, \unit{m/s}$$By kinematics, the pellet then rises an additional $$\Delta h = \frac{v^2}{2g}=\frac{13^2}{2\cdot 9.8}=8.62\, \unit m$$
        \item Note that the horizontal speed of the skeet is always $25\cdot \cos(28)=22.07\, \unit{m/s}$. The extra distance $\Delta x$ is equal to the extra time the skeet ends up in the air, times this horizontal speed. In the initial case the skeet just falls vertically from an initial vertical speed of 0, so we have $$h=\frac 12gt_1^2\Rightarrow t_1=\sqrt{\frac{2h}{g}}$$But now we need $h$, and we can find this via $h=v_y^2/2g=25^2\sin^2(28)/(2\cdot 9.8)=7.03\, \unit m.$ So in the case where the skeet doesn't get hit it would move for an extra time $$t_1=\sqrt{\frac{2h}{g}}=\sqrt{\frac{2\cdot 7.03}{9.8}}=1.2\, \unit s$$In the case where it does get hit, we have an initial velocity of 13 m/s upward, so by kinematics $$7.03=-13t_2+4.9t_2^2\Rightarrow t_2=3.11\, \unit s$$ by the quadratic formula (we take the positive root because time has to be positive). Then the extra distance is $\Delta x = v_x(t_2-t_1)=22.07(3.11-1.2)=42\, \unit m.$
    \end{anum}

