A pendulum consists of a block $M$ hanging at the bottom end of a massless rod of length l, which has a frictionless pivot at its top end. A mass $m$, moving at speed $v$, hits the block $M$ and gets embedded in the block. What is the minimum $v$ so that the entire system can move through a half-circle as shown, and swing back around?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{thing3}
    \end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
    \item By conservation of energy, the initial kinetic energy of the block-bullet system can be found via $$\frac 12(M+m)v^2=\frac 12 kx^2+(M+m)g\mu x\Rightarrow v= 0.917\, \unit{m/s}$$This is after the collision, so the initial speed $u$ of the bullet is found as $$v=\frac{mu}{M+m}\Rightarrow u=\frac{M+m}{m}v=917\, \unit{m/s}$$
    \item The initial kinetic energy is $(1/2)mu^2=420\, \unit{J}$ and the final kinetic energy is $(1/2)(M+m)v^2=0.42\, \unit{J}$. The fraction of the energy lost is then $(420-0.42)/420=0.999$. 
\end{anum}

problem:
A plank of mass $M$ and length $L$ is placed on a frictionless table, and a small block of mass $m$ is placed on the plank. The coefficient of friction between the block and the plank is $\mu$. Initially, the block is at the left end of the plank as shown but it suddenly gains a velocity $v_0$ to the right. What must $v_0$ be so that after a long time, the block will be at the right end of the plank?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{blockmove}
    \end{center}
    There is a quick solution by using conservation of momentum.

solution:
By conservation of momentum, the blocks must end up moving together at a speed $v = mv_0/(M + m)$. Their combined energy is therefore less, and the lost energy is equal to the work done by friction, $W_f = mg\mu L$. Hence,\begin{align*}
        mg\mu L&=\frac12mv_0^2-\frac12(M+m)\left(\frac{mv_0}{M+m}\right)^2\\
        mg\mu L&=\frac12mv_0^2-\frac12\frac{m^2}{M+m}v_0^2\\
        mg\mu L&=\frac12mv_0^2\left(1-\frac{m}{M+m}\right)\\
        L&=\frac{v_0^2}{2g\mu}\frac{M}{M+m}\\
        \Rightarrow v_0&=\boxed{\sqrt{2g\mu L\frac{M+m}{M}}}
    \end{align*}
